observations.recommendation:
Management reactivates or creates a new Inventory Committee composed of a representative each from the Mayor’s Office, from the Municipal Treasurer’s Office and a representative from each department to prepare the necessary procedures in the proper and orderly conduct of the physical count of the all the property, plant and equipment and inventories owned by the Municipality;

The Inventory Committee conducts the physical count of all the properties recorded in the books and those not yet recorded but actually found in the LGU offices/premises and to prepare the corresponding inventory reports thereof in accordance with the prescribed format (See Annex 49 - Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment) of the NGAS Manual; 

The inventory committee prepares and submits the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) and the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RCPI) to the Auditor, at least annually, after reconciliation with accounting records as provided by law and regulations.

Enjoin the Municipal Accountant to:
Effect the necessary correcting entries in order to update the Net Book Value of Property, Plant, and Equipment (PPE) in the financial position and reflect the accurate depreciation expense for PPE items identified in Annex F;
Trace the acquisition dates of previously acquired PPE accounts and recompute the carrying amounts by cross-referencing existing documents such as purchase orders, invoices, contracts, and other relevant records. For the current acquisition and onwards, maintain Property Ledger Card;
Direct the GSO to:
Conduct periodic inventory counts and physical inspections of the PPE items to determine their estimated acquisition dates and ensure keeping of complete PPE records with relevant data; and
Submit to the Municipal Accountant the data gathered for reconciliation.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Issue demand letters quarterly and instruct all accountable officers with outstanding unliquidated cash advances to settle their accounts within 15 days of receipt from receipt hereof, or else refund the full amount advanced, otherwise, administrative and criminal prosecution may be sought by management and/or the audit team;
Direct all responsible officials and employees to liquidated their cash advances within the reporting period and for the Accountant to monitor compliance hereof;
In the case of the deceased or those who have been separated from service, make representations with the proper prosecuting agencies of the government towards the institution of the necessary proceedings for the recovery of the amount of the cash advance as provided in Section 4.1 of COA Circular No. 86-256; and
File a request for authority to write-off for the accounts that are deemed dormant and liquidation is futile, to be guided by the procedures contained in COA Circular 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023.

The Municipal Accountant and all department heads comply with the provisions of Sections 51 and 114 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs specifically on the recording of supplies and materials as Inventories.

The Municipal Accountant keeps an updated Supplies Ledger Cards (SLC) and the Municipal Treasurer (in the absence of a General Services Officer) maintains Stock Cards for each inventory item received which should be reconciled with the SLC in the Accounting department;

The GSO prepares and submits the Report on the Supplies and Materials Issued monthly to the Accounting department for the recording of the utilization in the Journal Entry Voucher to adjust the Inventories accounts.

We recommend that management:

Reactivate or create a new Inventory Committee composed of a representative each from the Mayor’s Office, from the Municipal Treasurer’s Office and a representative from each department to prepare the necessary procedures in the proper and orderly conduct of the physical count of the all the property, plant and equipment and inventories owned by the Municipality;

Require the Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of all the properties recorded in the books and those not yet recorded but actually found in the LGU offices/premises and to prepare the corresponding inventory reports thereof in accordance with the prescribed format (See Annex 49 - Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment) of the NGAS Manual; 

Prepare and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) and the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RCPI) to the Auditor, at least annually, after reconciliation with accounting records as provided by law and regulations.

We reiterated our prior year’s audit recommendation that management:
Designate a full-time General Services Officer (GSO) who will be responsible for the preservation, maintenance, and safekeeping of the PPEs of the LGU;
Issue an executive order or internal memorandum identifying and requiring key employees or department heads to submit a timeline in adopting the one-time cleansing of PPE account balance, within 30 days from issuance of such order or memorandum;
Require the municipal accountant and the GSO to maintain separate ledger and property cards and ARE for acquisitions of PPE in C.Y. 2024 and conduct regular reconciliation pending the cleansing of the PPE account.
To expedite the physical inventory taking, issue an internal memorandum requiring each employee to submit every semester a list of LGU properties under their custody, and let this be a requirement before the payment of any enhancement or productivity bonus.

We recommended that management:
Direct the municipal treasurer and municipal accountant to reconcile the cash in-bank variances noted in their respective records;
Submit to the Office of the Auditor the Bank Reconciliation Statements for all bank accounts maintained within fifteen (15) days after the end of each month;
Pursue with vigor the enrolment of the local government to LBP’s weAccess and DBP’s Digital Banking Portal.

We recommended that management:
Initiate the execution of lease contracts on all market stallholders;
Dispose of the occupancy of the closed stalls and have them rented out to other vendors;
Pursue with vigor the issuance of Notices of Non-Payment and Closure which are the remedies for default under Sections 61 of the Ordinance;
Instruct the municipal accountant to prepare correcting entries on the operating lease receivable accountant and to take up the payments made by the stallholders in the succeeding years;
Consider having a dialogue with the market vendors which in part could include taking up the vendors’ request for a daily collection system.
Otherwise, we recommended that management enjoin the Sangguniang Bayan to review and amend the provisions of Municipal Ordinance No. 247, series of 2017 if both the executive and legislative departments find the relevant provisions governing the stall rentals of Clarin Town Center do not serve well the interest of the local government, the lessees, and the general public.

We recommended that management:
Instruct the municipal accountant to draw a correcting entry on the AP and Leave Benefits Payable accounts;
Set an earlier cut-off date for obligating transactions by year-end as a discipline measure to avoid voluminous transactions which could have been processed in earlier months or period.

We recommended that management:
Cease from granting additional cash advances unless the previous cash advance given to an accountable officer is initially settled or proper accounting thereof is made, and withhold the salaries of all accountable officers who are still connected with the LGU until settlement of their respective cash advances;
Send demand letters and instruct all accountable officers with outstanding unliquidated cash advances to liquidate their cash advances within 15 days from receipt hereof, or else refund the full amount advanced, otherwise, administrative and criminal prosecution may be sought by management and/or the audit team;
In the case of the deceased or those who have been separated from service, make representations with the proper prosecuting agencies of the government towards the institution of the necessary proceedings for the recovery of the amount of the cash advance as provided in Section 4.1 of COA Circular No. 86-256; and
File a request for authority to write-off for the accounts that are deemed dormant and liquidation is futile, to be guided by the procedures contained in COA Circular 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023.

We recommended that management:
Instruct the HRMO to immediately update in the GSIS portal the salary details of employees;
Advise the municipal accountant and HRMO to confer with GSIS on the reconciliation of unpaid premiums per individual accounts;
Confer with the GSIS management and the LGU employees on the best resolution for the unpaid premiums.

We recommended that management:
Direct the municipal assessor to prepare a financial and operational plan and requirements to carry out the tax mapping;
Enjoin the Sangguniang Bayan to support funding initiatives for the preparation of tax maps and subsequent related activities thereto.

We recommended that management instruct the Municipal Treasurer to:
Update the individual records of properties and submit to the Office of the Auditor an aging of the RPT and SET delinquencies as of December 31, 2023;
Comply with the posting requirements necessary for the collection of all delinquencies;
Submit to the accountant by year-end the List of RPT and SET delinquencies that can no longer be collected, as the basis for recognizing impairment loss;
Fast-track the data build up to enable the resumption of use of the ETHRACS.
Likewise, we recommended that management initiate availing of the administrative and/or judicial remedies for the collection delinquencies within the prescriptive period.

We recommended that management:
Instruct the municipal treasurer and the accountant to communicate to the Source Agencies (SAs) a written request for a copy of the MOA for the subject fund transfers;
Initiate the preparation of MOA between the NGAs, if such were not constituted on the subject fund transfers tied with specific purposes;
Direct the municipal engineer to coordinate and furnish the municipal accountant with the completion certificates and/or project status for those without readily available information;
Execute prompt implementation of projects funded by the NGAs;
Enjoin the focal person of each project to submit status reports and other relevant documents to assist in the liquidation of funds; and
Return to the SAs any unused funds of the completed projects as prescribed under COA Circular No. 94-013.

We recommended that management:
Consider revising the existing contingency plan on landslides providing an anatomy of the hazard that is distinct and uniquely formulated for landslides;
Enjoin the LDRRM Council to provide fund linkage between the mitigating measures and gaps identified in the contingency plan, to maximize the disaster preparedness of the local government.

We recommended that management:
Direct the municipal treasurer and accountant to immediately transfer the CY 2023 unexpended balance in the LDRRMF;
Enjoin the LDRRMO and the LDRRM Council to provide a more specific implementation timeline for PPAs in the LDRRMIP;
Require the LDRRMO to closely monitor the implementation of PPAs under the LDRRMIP and set a target of at least a 90% financial delivery rate on planned PPAs in CY 2024;
Instruct the LDRRMO to submit monthly to the Office of the Auditor the Report of Sources and Utilization of DRRMF on or before the 15th day after the end of each month.

We recommended that management:
Indorse the GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) to attend the training on the preparation and establishment of a GAD Database;
Enjoin the GFPS to conduct a re-echo training to the department heads and public officials on the information requirements of a GAD Database;
Identify key officials who will lead the establishment of a GAD Database;
Instruct the GFPS to submit to the Office of the Auditor an electronic or paper copy of the GAD Database for the year 2024.

We recommended to the management to:
Enjoin the Municipal Accountant to stop the granting of additional cash advance unless the previous cash advance given is first settled or proper accounting thereof is made;
Withhold the salaries of all accountable officers who are still connected with the LGU until settlement of their respective cash advances pursuant to Section 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002;
Send demand letters through a registered mail to those accountable officers who are not anymore connected with the LGU and/or cause the withholding of the amount due from the concerned officials and employees to compel them to settle their accounts. Management may resort to legal action if no settlement has been made after sending three (3) demand letters; and
File a request for authority to write-off for the accounts that are deemed dormant and liquidation is futile, to be guided by the procedures contained in COA Circular 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

We recommended to management the following:
Consider the creation of General Services Office (GSO) who will be responsible in the preservation, maintenance and safekeeping of the PPEs of the LGU;
Create an inventory committee composed of adequate number of members with at least one member each from the Accounting Unit and Supply Unit and enjoin them to conduct the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts of the Municipality in accordance with the prescribed procedures embodied in COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability;
After the conduct of inventory taking, direct the inventory committee to prepare and submit the following to the Audit Team in the prescribed format:
Report on Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE);
Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), if there are unserviceable properties found during inventory taking;
Request for Relief from Accountability by Accountable persons for lost PPE items under their accountability, if any;
Journal Entry Vouchers drawn by the Accounting Unit for recognition of loss of PPE from concerned accountable officers/personnel, if any, and other necessary adjusting entries;
Enjoin the Municipal Accountant to derecognize properties that do not qualify on the capitalization threshold of PPE and require the Supply Officer to prepare Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) for each recorded PPEs that are to be derecognized from PPE account due to capitalization threshold of PPE and ensure that future issuances of semi-expandable properties are issued with ICS and Property Acknowledgement Receipt (PAR) for property and equipment; and
Instruct the GSO to prepare yearly report of inventory of semi-expandable properties in order to monitor existence of the said properties.

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare adjusting entries to record the accountabilities of the barangays in the books of the municipality by debiting the ‘Due from LGUs’ account and crediting the ‘Due to LGUs’ account for the amount released to the barangays which remain unliquidated;

Demand liquidation with complete supporting documents from the beneficiary barangays on the utilization of the funds received and provide the appropriate accounting entries thereof;

Ensure that the fund is duly covered with Memorandum of Agreement with the beneficiary barangays; and

Refrain from receiving financial assistance intended for its barangays, instead require the latter to enter into agreement with the source agency in the exercise of its local autonomy.

Implement the accrual basis of recognizing revenue to conform with the International Public Sector Accounting Standards;

Revisit the pro-forma lease contract and consider amendments on above-noted deficiencies; and

Enhance ledger cards to show the unpaid balance at any given time and other relevant data.

Find ways to look for sources of fund for the supplemental appropriation of the unpaid electricity expense with a total amount of ₱989,395.92 as of December 31, 2020 in order to stop the agency’s practice of charging prior years’ expenditure to current year appropriation;

Enjoin the Municipal Budget Officer to strictly follow budget procedure and ensure that utility expenses are automatically included in the yearly budget appropriation;

Require the Municipal Accountant to take up in the books expenditures and obligations incurred during the current period so as to reflect the correct pertinent account in the financial statements;

Ensure that electricity bills are paid on time to avoid incurrence of surcharges, otherwise officials and employees responsible for the delay shall be personally liable for any disallowance arising therefrom;

Enjoin the Municipal Treasurer to strictly implement the collection policy of electric bills due to the stall lessees; and

Strictly enforce the provision in the Contract of Lease between LGU Clarin and the stall lessees of the Clarin Town Center stalls on the installation of separate electric meter for every stall in the Clarin Town Center to ease the burden on the part of the Municipality from the delinquent lessees.

Reconcile the SAP beneficiaries paid by the LGU with the DSWD database and provide the DSWD Field Office 10 the updated/corrected SAP-1 database having a total of 4,648 heads of the family;

Submit to the Office of the Auditor the list of the 429 lacking SAP beneficiaries in the DSWD database with complete data as shown in the social amelioration cards;

Organize a validation team who will work in close coordination with barangay officials concerned and the MSWDO to conduct verification on the eligibility of the aforementioned 51 beneficiaries based on the filled out Social Amelioration Cards; and 




Direct the validation team to submit to the audit team a report/status of their verification and the actions taken by management and liable persons thereon.

Require the Accounting Office to debit the Inventory account upon purchases and credit the same upon distribution or receipt of Report of Supplies and Materials Issued (RSMI) from the GSO/end users;

Require the Municipal Accountant to adjust the noted deficiencies by recognizing the identified equipment in the books of the Municipality, and ensure that equipment purchased together with supplies, are correctly classified in the books;

Require the Supply Officer to take supervision and control over all delivered supplies and materials carried in stock by the LGU and observe the correct forms in issuing supplies, materials and PPE;

Direct the Supply Officer to summarize monthly the issued RIS in the RSMI to be submitted to the Accounting Office as basis in recognizing the expense accounts; and

Require the periodic physical inventory of supplies and materials. Physical count of unissued inventory items by type shall be conducted at least once a year and reported in the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) and submit the same to the Auditor not later than January 31 of each year.

Establish a sound and clear policies and procedures in renting out its heavy equipment taking into consideration the persons responsible from the preparation of lease contract up to the receipt of payment in order to attain the LGU’s target income from the lease of heavy equipment; 

Ensure that all lease of heavy equipment are covered with written lease contract with a fair and reasonable terms with due consideration of the Municipal Revenue Code; and

Require the Equipment-In-Charge to prepare Monthly Report on Heavy Equipment Utilization and submit the same to the auditor.

Enjoin the Municipal Accountant to trace the recorded transactions and reconcile accounting records to that of the Municipal Agriculture Office data. Further, prepare and maintain the Work, Other Animals and Breeding Stocks Ledger Card (WOABSLC) as provided under Sections 114 of the NGAS Manual;

Enjoin the Municipal Agriculturist to coordinate with the source Agency, the Department of Agriculture, and secure pertinent official documents relative to the terms and conditions of the animal dispersal projects to identify propriety over the livestock; and

Require the GSO Designate to include in the conduct of physical inventory the breeding stocks/animals with the assistance from the Municipal Agriculture Office for easy identification of the breeding stocks.

Enjoin the Inventory Committee to conduct complete physical inventory count over the LGU’s Property, Plant and Equipment and Biological assets and submit the RPCPPE and QRBA to the Office of the Auditor and other office concerned;

Direct the GSO to coordinate with the Municipal Engineer to prepare the road map of the Municipality to facilitate the preparation of a proper inventory and reporting of the Municipality’s road network system; and

Direct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects.

Expedite implementation and completion of the projects in accordance with the guidelines stated in memorandum of agreement with source agency for timely benefit to constituents; 


Instruct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to conduct reconciliation of records with source agency for proper recognition of fund transfer balances and full liquidation;


Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to return to source agencies all unexpended fund balances on all completed projects, otherwise to request for authority to realign said balances for other priority projects; and

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to draw journal entry voucher to record the return as evidenced by the source agency’s official receipt; make reclassification entry to properly recognize the assets on completed projects; and close trust liability accounts on funds duly liquidated.

